com.bluegosling.tuples

Class NTuple<A,B,C,D,E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bluegosling.tuples.NTuple<A,B,C,D,E>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - the type of the first item
    B - the type of the second item
    C - the type of the third item
    D - the type of the fourth item
    E - the type of the fifth item
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Tuple, Tuple.Ops1<A>, Tuple.Ops2<A,B>, Tuple.Ops3<A,B,C>, Tuple.Ops4<A,B,C,D>, Tuple.Ops5<A,B,C,D,E>, Serializable, Iterable<Object>

    public class NTuple<A,B,C,D,E>
extends Object
implements Tuple.Ops5<A,B,C,D,E>, Serializable
    A tuple that has more than five elements. It is so named since it can have n number of elements (where n > 5).

    To prevent the number of generic type arguments from getting out of hand and becoming unwieldy, this provides type safety (and rich API) only for the first 5 elements. Access to other elements in the tuple can be had using the list or array forms.

    See Also:

        public Tuple.Ops5<B,C,D,E,?> removeFirst()
        Removes the first item from the tuple. Since tuples are immutable, this returns a new tuple with one less item.

        If this tuple has exactly six elements, then the returned tuple will have five elements and thus be an instance of Quintet. If this tuple has more than six elements, then the returned tuple will also be an NTuple.

      • get

        public Object get(int index)
        Retrieves an item from the tuple using its index. This is required to access items in the tuple beyond the fifth. Indices are zero-based, so a value of zero would be the same as calling getFirst().

      • insert

        public NTuple<?,?,?,?,?> insert(int index,
                                Object o)
        Inserts the specified value at the given index. Since tuples are immutable, this returns a new tuple with the added element. Any items at or after the given index will be pushed out so that they appear after the newly added element in the resulting tuple. Indices are zero-based, so a value of zero would be the same as calling insertFirst(Object).
        Parameters:

        Throws:

      • remove

        public Tuple.Ops5<?,?,?,?,?> remove(int index)
        Removes the value at the given index. Since tuples are immutable, this returns a new tuple with the element removed. Indices are zero-based, so a value of zero would be the same as calling removeFirst().

        If this tuple has exactly six elements, then the returned tuple will have five elements and thus be an instance of Quintet. If this tuple has more than six elements, then the returned tuple will also be an NTuple.

        Parameters:
        index - the zero-based index of the item to remove
        Returns:
        a new tuple that is identical to this tuple except it has one fewer item due to the item at the given index being removed
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the given index is less than zero or is greater than or equal to the tuple's size()

      • toArray

        public <T> T[] toArray(T[] a)
        Description copied from interface: Tuple
        Returns an array of the items in this tuple. The runtime type of the returned array is that of the specified array. If the tuple's elements fits in the specified array, they are returned therein. Otherwise, a new array is allocated with the runtime type of the specified array and the size of this collection.

        If this tuple fits in the specified array with room to spare (i.e., the array has more elements than this tuple), the element in the array immediately following the last element of the tuple is set to null. (This is useful in determining the length of this tuple only if the caller knows that this tuple does not contain any null elements.)

        Specified by:
        toArray in interface Tuple
        Parameters:
